description: PUH-BrianMartell The Tension Field: Deriving Newton’s Inverse Square Law from Soliton Gradients — Understandable Explanation The soliton (particle) is a localized twist knot in the E8 lattice. This knot stretches surrounding strands, creating a radial tension gradient ξ(r) that falls off with distance. Simple picture: •  At the knot center: Maximum twist → high ξ. •  Far away: Twist relaxes → ξ approaches background. •  In 3D lattice, twist spreads over spherical shells → energy density ~1/r^4, force (gradient) ~1/r^2. •  Gravity = lattice “pull” trying to untwist the knot → attracts other knots. Electron Twist Radius Calculation Classical electron radius r_e ≈ 2.82 × 10^{-15} m (e² / (4πε₀ m c²)). In PUH, this is the effective soliton core where twist ξ exceeds lattice yield — the “knot size.”
